{{For|the grid computing network|DiaGrid (distributed computing network)}} [[Image:Swiss.re.arp.750pix.jpg|thumb|Base of [[30 St Mary Axe]], London, UK]] [[File:Worlds First Diagrid Hyperboloid by Shukhov 1896.jpg|thumb|The [[world's first hyperboloid structure|world's first diagrid hyperboloid structure]] in [[Polibino, Dankovsky District, Lipetsk Oblast|Polibino]], Russia]] [[Image:Myzeil-knippershelbig-02.jpg|thumb|[[MyZeil]], Frankfurt, Germany]] [[File:CCTV Headquarters (6349184617).jpg|thumb|[[CCTV Headquarters]], Beijing, China]]
The '''diagrid''' (a [[portmanteau]] of '''diagonal grid''') is a framework of diagonally intersecting metal, concrete or wooden beams that is used in the construction of buildings and roofs.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ian Volner|title=Dissecting Diagrid|journal=Architect|date=5 October 2011|url=http://www.architectmagazine.com/structure/dissecting-diagrid.aspx|publisher=American Institute of Architects|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119015948/http://www.architectmagazine.com/structure/dissecting-diagrid.aspx|archivedate=19 November 2011|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> It requires less [[structural steel]] than a conventional [[steel frame]]. [[Hearst Tower (New York City)|Hearst Tower]] in New York City, designed by [[Norman Foster, Baron Foster of Thames Bank|Norman, Lord Foster]], uses 21 percent less steel than a standard design.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/07/nyregion/hearst-tower-echoes-trade-center-plan.html|title=Hearst Tower Echoes Trade Center Plan|author=David W. Dunlap|date=7 October 2004|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> The diagrid obviates the need for columns and can be used to make large column-free expanses of roofing.<ref name="Boake2014">{{cite book|author=Terri Meyer Boake|title=Diagrid Structures: Systems, Connections, Details|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H67mBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|date=23 January 2014|publisher=Birkhäuser|isbn=978-3-03821-482-3|pages=13–}}</ref> Another iconic building designed by Lord Foster, [[30 St Mary Axe]], known as "The Gherkin", also uses the diagrid system.
British architect [[Ian Ritchie (architect)|Ian Ritchie]] wrote in 2012: {{cquote|The origin of 'diagonal' structures is surely the Russian genius Vladimir Shukhov. He pioneered new analytical methods in many different fields, and I have been fortunate to visit some of his constructed projects more than once. Shukhov left a lasting legacy to early Soviet Russia constructivism, and as the leading engineer and mathematician during the late 19th and early 20th century he created hyperboloid, thin shell and tensile structures of extraordinary refinement and elegance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-architect.co.uk/articles/diagonal_structures.htm|title=Diagonal Structures, Diagrid Structure|author=Ian Ritchie|publisher=e-architect|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>}}
== Buildings utilizing diagrid == * [[Shukhov Tower in Polibino]], Polibino, Russia (1896) * [[Shukhov Rotunda]] at the [[All-Russia exhibition 1896|All-Russia exhibition]], Nizhny Novgorod, Russia (1896) * [http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Double_curvature_steel_lattice_Shell_by_Shukhov_in_Vyksa_1897_shell.jpg The world's first double curvature steel diagrid roof], Vyksa, Russia, (1897) {{cn|date=May 2017}} * [[Shukhov Tower]], Moscow, Russia * [[Hearst Tower (Manhattan)|Hearst Tower]], New York, USA * [[30 St Mary Axe]], London, England * [[1 The Avenue]], Manchester, England * [[CCTV Headquarters]], Beijing, China * [[The Bow (Calgary)|The Bow]], Calgary, Canada * [[Seattle Central Library]], Seattle, USA * [[Capital Gate]], Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates * [[Aldar headquarters building|Aldar headquarters]], Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates * [[Guangzhou International Finance Center]], Guangzhou, China * [[Queen Elizabeth II Great Court]] at the [[British Museum]], London, England * [[Nagoya Dome]], Nagoya, Japan * [http://www.e-architect.co.uk/helsinki/korkeasaari-island-lookout-tower Korkeasaari Lookout Tower], Helsinki, Finland * [[Westhafen Tower]], Frankfurt, Germany * [[MyZeil]], Frankfurt, Germany * [[The Crystal, Copenhagen|The Crystal]], Copenhagen, Denmark * [http://www.sbp.de/en/project/botanical-garden-shanghai/ Botanical Garden Shanghai], Shanghai, China * [http://www.sbp.de/en/project/glass-roofs-paunsdorf-center/ Paunsdorf Center], Leipzig, Germany * [http://www.createltd.co.nz/project-view/the-coastlands-aquatic-centre-kapiti/ Coastlands Aquatic Centre], Kapiti, New Zealand * [http://www.architectureanddesign.com.au/news/south-australian-health-and-medical-research-insti South Australian Health and Medical Research Institute], Adelaide, Australia * [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:King's_Cross_Western_Concourse_-_central_position_-_2012-05-02.75.jpg Departures concourse] at [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross railway station]], London, England * [https://www.emporis.com/buildings/121909/united-steelworkers-building-pittsburgh-pa-usa United Steelworkers Building], Pittsburgh, USA * [[Tornado Tower]], Doha, Qatar * [http://www.illumni.co/macquarie-bank-one-shelley-st-king-st-wharf-sydney-by-vision-design/ One Shelley Street], Sydney, Australia * [http://www.aurecongroup.com/en/projects/property/mit-manukau-campus-and-transport-interchange.aspx Transport interchange] at the [[Manukau Institute of Technology]], Otara, New Zealand * [http://www.willmottdixon.co.uk/news/the-living-planet-centre-will-showcase-wwfs-conservation-work-to-the-world The WWF Living Planet Centre], Woking, England * [[Newfoundland Quay]], London, England
